old_names: Respond when name is called (e.g., by turning and looking at source).
Respond to "no no" (by stopping what he/she is doing, at least for a moment).
React to "there's mommy/daddy" by looking around for them.
Want to go for a ride?

Some children like to "parrot" or imitate things that they've just heard (including new words that they are just learning, and/or parts of sentences, for example, repeating "work now" after mother says "Mommy's going to work now.") How often does your children imitate words?
Some children like to go around naming or labeling things, as though proud of knowing the names and wanting to show this. How often does your child do this?
Extends arm to show you something he/she is holding.
Reaches out and gives you a toy or some object that he/she is holding.
Points (with arm and index finger extended) at some interesting object or event.
Waves bye-bye on his/her own when someone leaves.
Extends his/her arm upward to signal a wish to be picked up.
Gestures "hush" by placing finger to lips.
Requests something by extending arm and opening and closing hand.
Smacks lips in a "yum yum" gesture to indicate that something tastes good.
Shrugs to indicate "all gone" or "where'd it go."
Drink from a cup containing liquid.
Wipe face or hands with a towel or cloth.
Put on necklace, bracelet or watch.
Lay head on hands and squeeze eyes shut as if sleeping.
Blow to indicate something is hot.
Pour pretend liquid from one container to another.
Stir pretend liquid in a cup or pan with a spoon.
Try to put shoe or sock or hat on it.
Try to put diaper on it.
Put key in door or lock.
Write with pen or pencil or marker.
